title: Auchmill Community Woodland
description: 8.8 hectares woodland located between Bucksburn and Heathryfold

title: Brimmond Hill
description: The summit is the highest point in Aberdeen City

title: Coastal Footpath from Cove to Nigg
description: A rocky coastline leading from the small harbour in Cove, which is a good seabird watching point, especially skuas and sea terns.

title: Persley Walled Garden
description: Small well-kept garden overlooking the River Don

title: Den of Maidencraig Local Nature Reserve
description: An interesting site with grassland, wetland and ancient marshy woodland habitats. Excellent for birdwatching, pond dipping (from platform), and dog walking. Foxes and roe deer are sometimes spotted.

title: Donmouth Local Nature Reserve
description: River estuary with easy access walking paths.

title: Four Hills Walks (Brimmond, Elrick, Kirkhill, & Tyrebagger hills)
description: A forest trail, bedecked by modern art installations, with a visit to the more open and natural landscape of Elrick Hill.

title: Hazlehead Woods
description: The largest park in Aberdeen, with regular events such as highland games, american football.  Plenty of children's play area, and there is a horse riding school.  A memorial to the Piper Alpha tragedy is located here.

title: Nigg Bay Site of Special Scientific Interest
Pot Heugh
description: Woodland situated just below the former Craiginches Prison in Torry.

title: Tullos Hill and Community Woodland
description: Rough grassland, heathland, scrub and woodland that contains no less than 13 cairns. A varied walking experience with chance to see local wildlife.

title: Walker Dam
description: Charming and scenic area for wildlife

title: Shri Bheemas Indian Restaurant Bridge of Don
East St Nicholas
description: Also known as the Mither Kirk, it was built in 1835-37. Architect Archibald Simpson.

title: The Tolbooth
description: built in 1616-1629. The Tolbooth houses the Aberdeen Museum of Civic History

title: Mercat Cross
description: Sandstone market cross built in 1686 by John Montgomery. The structure is the finest and best preserved 17thC market crosses, and is situated in Castlegate at the top end of Union Street.

title: King’s College
description: first built in 1500.  Since then has been through several additions and modifications.

title: Provost Skene's House
description: built in 1545. Temporarily closed during construction work on Marischal Square.

title: Robert Gordon’s Hospital
description: built in 1731; modified in 1833 by John Smith. Now a secondary school Robert Gordon’s College.

title: Marischal College
description: founded in 1593, rebuilt in 1891 by A Marshall Mackenzie. It is the 2nd largest granite frontage in world after Escorial in Madrid.

title: St Katharine’s Centre / The Lemon Tree
description: 1937 Jenkins & Marr. Modern art deco style architecture.

title: Maritime Museum, Shiprow
description: 1996/97 incl. 16thC Provost Ross House & 19thC Trinity Congregational Church

title: Faculty of Management & Design Library – RGIT Faculty of Management 1998, Foster & Partners
description: 1998 Foster & Partners. £18m building for Robert Gordon University features a dramatic curved steel roof.

title: Scott Sutherland School of Architecture – Tower Building
description: Dixon.Jones Architects. Postmodern architecture influence from Aldo Rossi and local Castles.

title: Aberdeen Harbour Masters’ Tower
description: 2006 SMC Parr Architects. Marine Operations Centre run by Aberdeen Harbour Authority.
